  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Money laundering is a serious federal offense in the United States, and the penalties can be severe. The primary statutes governing money laundering are found in the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957). Below are the key penalties associated with money laundering under federal law:\n\n### **1. Money Laundering (18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956)**\n   - **Penalties for Violation**:\n     - **Imprisonment**: Up to **20 years** per count.\n     - **Fines**: Up to **$500,000** **or** twice the value of the laundered funds, whichever is greater.\n   - **Enhanced Penalties**:\n     - If the money laundering involves proceeds from certain specified unlawful activities (e.g., drug trafficking, terrorism), the penalties can be more severe.\n     - If the offense is related to international terrorism, the maximum prison term increases to **25 years**.\n\n### **2. Engaging in Monetary Transactions in Property Derived from Specified Unlawful Activity (18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957)**\n   - This statute applies to transactions involving criminally derived property worth more than **$10,000**, regardless of intent to launder.\n   - **Penalties for Violation**:\n     - **Imprisonment**: Up to **10 years**.\n     - **Fines**: Up to **$250,000** or twice the value of the property involved.\n\n### **3. Civil and Administrative Penalties**\n   - In addition to criminal penalties, individuals and entities involved in money laundering may face **civil fines**, **asset forfeiture**, and other administrative sanctions such as the loss of professional licenses.\n\n### **4. Forfeiture Provisions**\n   - Under 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 981 and 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 982, the government can seize and forfeit assets involved in or derived from money laundering activities.\n\n### **Factors Influencing Penalties**\n   - The severity of the penalties can depend on:\n     - The amount of money involved.\n     - The nature of the underlying criminal activity (e.g., drug trafficking, terrorism, fraud).\n     - The defendant\u2019s role in the scheme (e.g., organizer vs. minor participant).\n     - Whether the defendant cooperated with law enforcement.\n\n### **International Money Laundering**\n   - If the money laundering involves international transactions or violates the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)**, additional penalties may apply, including enhanced fines and forfeitures.\n\n### **Example Cases**\n   - Individuals convicted of money laundering have faced sentences ranging from **5 to 20 years** in prison, depending on the scale and nature of the offense.\n   - Corporations involved in money laundering can face fines in the **millions or even billions of dollars**, as well as reputational damage and loss of business.\n\nIf you or someone you know is facing money laundering charges, it is critical to consult with a qualified federal criminal defense attorney to understand the specific legal options and potential consequences.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
